<subSubSection id="C305EAC06900FFDEFC98F9536250FEF9" lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="108" pageId="17" pageNumber="107" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BA0B94B6900FFDEFC98F9536250FEF9" blockId="17.[151,1437,1528,2023]" lastBlockId="18.[151,1437,153,287]" lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="108" pageId="17" pageNumber="107">
<emphasis id="B96B65596900FFDDFC98F953673EF90D" bold="true" box="[199,308,1745,1771]" pageId="17" pageNumber="107">Remarks</emphasis>
: This species was described by 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8EC4BA6900FFDDFECAF9536533F90D" author="Calvert, P. P." box="[661,825,1745,1771]" pageId="17" pageNumber="107" pagination="73 - 280" refId="ref11549" refString="Calvert, P. P. (1909) Contributions to a knowledge of the Odonata of the Neotropical region, exclusive of Mexico and Central America. Annals of the Carnegie Museum, 6 (3), 73 - 280." type="journal article" year="1909">Calvert (1909)</bibRefCitation>
from Iquitos (
<collectingCountry id="F308F9DB6900FFDDFF88F9536204F90D" box="[983,1038,1745,1771]" name="Peru" pageId="17" pageNumber="107">Peru</collectingCountry>
) based on a male and a female from Hagen´s collection. Calvert provided a very simple illustration of male cerci in laterodorsal view, which depicts the distance between bifurcation of medial process and tip of cerci as close to one half the length of cerci. 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8EC4BA6900FFDDF944F89B66E8F8B1" author="Williamson, E. B." pageId="17" pageNumber="107" pagination="1 - 88" refId="ref12284" refString="Williamson, E. B. (1919) Results of the University of Michigan - Williamson expedition to Colombia, 1916 - 17. IV. Notes on species of the genus Heteragrion Selys with descriptions of new species (Odonata). Occasional Papers of the Museum of Zoology, University of Michigan, 68, 1 - 88. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. part. 14454" type="journal article" year="1919">Williamson (1919)</bibRefCitation>
examined the type material (only the male, the female was lost) and discussed the possibility of a synonymy between 
<taxonomicName id="4C1FC2C86900FFDDFCA2F8E06770F89D" authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1862" box="[253,378,1890,1915]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Heteragrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="17" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="icterops">
<emphasis id="B96B65596900FFDDFCA2F8E06770F89D" box="[253,378,1890,1915]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="107">H. icterops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C1FC2C86900FFDDFDEBF8E0640DF89D" authorityName="Calvert" authorityYear="1909" box="[436,519,1890,1915]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Heteragrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="17" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inca">
<emphasis id="B96B65596900FFDDFDEBF8E0640DF89D" box="[436,519,1890,1915]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="107">H. inca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Williamson did not put much attention to caudal appendages and replicated the not very informative illustration of 
<taxonomicName id="4C1FC2C86900FFDDFE7EF8046478F879" authorityName="Calvert" authorityYear="1909" box="[545,626,1926,1951]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Heteragrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="17" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inca">
<emphasis id="B96B65596900FFDDFE7EF8046478F879" box="[545,626,1926,1951]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="107">H. inca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
cerci by Calvert, but he gave a good illustration of color pattern of head. The 
<typeStatus id="54A407E96900FFDDFC96F82B6721F825" box="[201,299,1961,1987]" pageId="17" pageNumber="107">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="4C1FC2C86900FFDDFD11F8286795F825" authorityName="Calvert" authorityYear="1909" box="[334,415,1962,1987]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Heteragrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="17" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inca">
<emphasis id="B96B65596900FFDDFD11F8286795F825" box="[334,415,1962,1987]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="107">H. inca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
seems to be lost (Rosser Garrison pers. comm. 2018), however, color pattern of head, which is very conspicuous, and the detailed and accurate description of coloration by Calvert, have allowed to identify a species that matches all these characteristics and occurs in the same region. Despite, cerci differ from Calvert`s (1909) illustration, because the middle process is located more distally, at approximately 3/4 of cerci length (
<figureCitation id="1324A5CE6903FFDEF930FF3F66B8FF1D" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1699,1724]" captionTargetBox="[353,1227,569,1672]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[349,1237,561,1680]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 10. Male cerci: H. inca: Orito, Putumayo (A) dorsal view (B) mediodorsal view (C) lateral view. Heteragrion m. atroterminatum: Union Panamericana, Chocó (D) dorsal view (E) mediodorsal view (F) lateral view. Heteragrion m. mitratum: Puerto Berrio, Antioquia (G) dorsal view (H) mediodorsal view (I) lateral view. VbC: Ventro basal convexity." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3253598/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="108">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
A–C), we believe these specimens represent 
<taxonomicName id="4C1FC2C86903FFDEFEFBFF6064FCFF1D" authorityName="Calvert" authorityYear="1909" box="[676,758,226,251]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Heteragrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="18" pageNumber="108" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inca">
<emphasis id="B96B65596903FFDEFEFBFF6064FCFF1D" box="[676,758,226,251]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="108">H. inca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8EC4BA6903FFDEFF5CFF636219FF1D" author="Bota-Sierra, C. A. &amp; Moreno-Arias, C. &amp; Faasen, T." box="[771,1043,224,251]" pageId="18" pageNumber="108" pagination="249 - 268" refId="ref11475" refString="Bota-Sierra, C. A., Moreno-Arias, C. &amp; Faasen, T. (2015) Preliminary list of Odonata from the Colombian Amazon, with descriptions of Inpabasis nigridorsum sp. nov. &amp; Diaphlebia richteri sp. nov. (Coenagrionidae &amp; Gomphidae). International Journal of Odonatology, 18 (3), 249 - 268. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 13887890.2015.1081637" type="journal article" year="2015">
Bota-Sierra 
<emphasis id="B96B65596903FFDEFFD4FF6065C8FF1D" box="[907,962,225,251]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="108">et al.</emphasis>
(2015)
</bibRefCitation>
reported 
<taxonomicName id="4C1FC2C86903FFDEF822FF6062C4FF1D" authorityName="Calvert" authorityYear="1909" box="[1149,1230,226,251]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Heteragrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="18" pageNumber="108" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inca">
<emphasis id="B96B65596903FFDEF822FF6062C4FF1D" box="[1149,1230,226,251]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="108">H. inca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="F308F9DB6903FFDEF94DFF63638AFF1D" box="[1298,1408,225,251]" name="Colombia" pageId="18" pageNumber="108">Colombia</collectingCountry>
in 
<collectingRegion id="49DB77A96903FFDEFCC8FE876796FEF9" box="[151,412,261,287]" country="Colombia" name="Amazonas" pageId="18" pageNumber="108">Amazonas Department</collectingRegion>
. Here, we report this species also from 
<collectingRegion id="49DB77A96903FFDEFF0AFE87625CFEF9" box="[853,1110,261,287]" country="Colombia" name="Putumayo" pageId="18" pageNumber="108">Putumayo Department</collectingRegion>
.
</paragraph>
